🧠 First: They Are BOTH Present

In Ruby on Rails, the middleware stack includes:

ActionDispatch::DebugExceptions

ActionDispatch::ShowExceptions

In both development and production.

They are not removed.

Their behavior changes.

🔥 How It Actually Works

The key config is:

config.consider_all_requests_local

🟢 In Development
config.consider_all_requests_local = true


What happens?

DebugExceptions shows the detailed error page

Stack trace

Code snippet

Params

Session

Full debugging UI

That big red Rails error screen 👇
This is DebugExceptions.

ShowExceptions is still there, but the debug one takes priority.

🔴 In Production
config.consider_all_requests_local = false


Now:

DebugExceptions does NOT show the debug page

ShowExceptions renders:

404 page

500 page

Usually from:

/public/404.html
/public/500.html


Or your custom exceptions_app.

🧠 So Your Statement Needs Slight Correction

You said:

DebugExceptions won’t work in production
ShowExceptions won’t work in development

More accurate version:

In development, DebugExceptions renders detailed error pages.
In production, ShowExceptions renders user-friendly error pages like 404 and 500.
Both middlewares are present in both environments, but their behavior depends on configuration.

That is the correct explanation.

🔥 Internal Flow (Production)
Exception occurs
     ↓
DebugExceptions passes it through
     ↓
ShowExceptions catches it
     ↓
Maps to status code
     ↓
Renders static error page

🔥 Internal Flow (Development)
Exception occurs
     ↓
DebugExceptions catches it
     ↓
Renders debug screen

🎯 Interview-Perfect Answer

If interviewer asks:

Do these middlewares work only in specific environments?

You answer:

Both DebugExceptions and ShowExceptions exist in all environments, but in development DebugExceptions renders the detailed error page, while in production ShowExceptions handles the exception and renders user-friendly 404 or 500 responses.

